historically and has paved the way for many enhanced algorithms such as adapt VQE.

4
00:21.520 --> 00:28.320
And finally, VQE is fairly simple. It's easy to understand what the quantum and classical computers do in this algorithm

5
00:28.320 --> 00:34.640
and how they interact. There are four main components of a VQE calculation.

6
00:34.640 --> 00:40.879
First, there's an operator, often a Hamiltonian, which we'll call H, that describes a property of the system that

7
00:40.879 --> 00:47.280
you wish to optimize. Another way of saying this is that you're seeking the igen vector of this operator that

8
00:47.280 --> 00:54.160
corresponds to the minimum IGEN value. We often call that igen vector the ground state.

9
00:54.160 --> 01:02.320
Next, there's an anzz word meaning approach. This is a quantum circuit that prepares a quantum state approximating

10
01:02.320 --> 01:09.360
the igen vector you're seeking. Really, the Anzots is a family of quantum circuits because some of the gates in

11
01:09.360 --> 01:18.159
the Anzots are parameterized. That is, they are fed a parameter which we can vary. This family of quantum circuits

12
01:18.159 --> 01:23.280
can prepare a family of quantum states approximating the ground state.

13
01:23.280 --> 01:32.000
Next, we need an estimator, a means of estimating the expectation value of the operator H over the current variational

14
01:32.000 --> 01:38.159
quantum state. Sometimes what we really care about is simply this expectation value, which we

15
01:38.159 --> 01:44.960
call a cost function. Other times we care about a more complicated function that can still be written starting from

16
01:44.960 --> 01:48.079
one or more expectation values.

17
01:48.079 --> 01:56.000
Finally, we need a classical optimizer, an algorithm that varies parameters to try to minimize this cost function.

18
01:56.000 --> 02:02.240
Let's outline the problem we want to solve and the general approach before addressing how quantum plays a role. We

19
02:02.240 --> 02:10.239
can cast many optimization problems critical to science and industry as matrix value problems. Commonly, you

20
02:10.239 --> 02:17.599
want the minimum igen value of your matrix and the igen vector that corresponds to it. The matrix H could be

21
02:17.599 --> 02:24.879
a Hamiltonian describing the energy of a physical system. And the minimum igen value would be the ground state energy

22
02:24.879 --> 02:33.120
E0 and the igen vector would be the corresponding quantum ground state often denoted SI sub0.

23
02:33.120 --> 02:40.720
Or the matrix could describe a complicated cost function associated with combinatorial optimization problems

24
02:40.720 --> 02:47.519
such as in logistics and the igen state s subopt would be an optimal solution of

25
02:47.519 --> 02:54.959
the problem like a binary string labeling a cut in a graph of a distribution network. In practice it's

26
02:54.959 --> 03:02.000
common to hear the term Hamiltonian used for all matrices of interest even outside the physical sciences. Let's say

27
03:02.000 --> 03:09.200
we're interested in a matrix with n rows and n columns. Such problems can be solved quickly and exactly using

28
03:09.200 --> 03:16.720
classical solvers for n up to a few hundred or thousand with no assumptions made about the matrix. For sparse

29
03:16.720 --> 03:24.400
matrices, those with mostly zeros as entries, this can be much larger with n as high as a billion even on a laptop.

30
03:24.400 --> 03:31.120
But for truly enormous problems that exceed these numbers, approximate or heristic methods are often required.

31
03:31.120 --> 03:39.840
The larger the matrix and the less sparse, the less tractable the problem and the more clever tricks must be employed. Suppose your matrix is so

32
03:39.840 --> 03:47.599
large that exact diagonalization is not an option. Suppose further that you know enough about your problem that you can

33
03:47.599 --> 03:54.799
make some guesses about the overall structure of the target state and you want to probe states similar to your

34
03:54.799 --> 04:02.480
initial guess to see if your cost or energy can be lowered further. This is a variational approach and it's one method

35
04:02.480 --> 04:10.879
that is used when exact diagonalization is not an option using a classical computer. This would work as follows.

36
04:10.879 --> 04:16.720
First, you make a guess state with some parameters theta that you will vary.

37
04:16.720 --> 04:23.120
Although this initial guess could be random, that is not advisable. We want to use knowledge of the problem at hand

38
04:23.120 --> 04:26.320
to tailor our guess as much as possible.

39
04:26.320 --> 04:33.120
Second, we would calculate the expectation value of the operator with the system in that state.

40
04:33.120 --> 04:37.360
Third, we would alter the variational parameters and repeat.

41
04:37.360 --> 04:45.360
Fourth, we would use accumulated information about the landscape of possible states in your variational subspace to make better and better

