04:49.040 --> 04:56.240
The variational principle guarantees that our variational state cannot yield an igen value lower than that of the

44
04:56.240 --> 05:03.520
target ground state. So the lower the expectation value, the better our approximation of the ground state. Let's

45
05:03.520 --> 05:07.600
talk about the difficulty of each step in this approach.

46
05:07.600 --> 05:14.560
Setting or updating parameters is computationally easy. The difficulty there is in selecting useful physically

47
05:14.560 --> 05:22.320
motivated initial parameters. Using accumulated information from prior iterations to update parameters in such

48
05:22.320 --> 05:28.880
a way that you approach the ground state is non-trivial. But classical optimization algorithms exist that do

49
05:28.880 --> 05:35.360
this quite efficiently. This classical optimization is only expensive because it may require many

50
05:35.360 --> 05:42.000
iterations. In the worst case, the number of iterations may scale exponentially with n.

51
05:42.000 --> 05:49.520
The most computationally expensive single step is almost certainly the expectation value of your matrix using a

52
05:49.520 --> 05:57.199
given state. The n byn matrix must act on the n element vector which corresponds to order n squared

53
05:57.199 --> 06:04.400
multiplication operations in the worst case. This must be done at each iteration of parameters. For extremely

54
